---
import BlogLayout from '../../../layouts/BlogLayout.astro';
const faq = [
  {"q": "Do I really need to learn keigo?", "a": "Yes, if you plan to use Japanese in any professional or social context. Even basic keigo (teineigo/です・ます form) is expected in shops, restaurants, and workplaces. Without it, you may unintentionally come across as rude or childish. Full keigo (sonkeigo + kenjougo) becomes essential for business and formal situations."},
  {"q": "What are the three types of keigo?", "a": "Sonkeigo (尊敬語) elevates others' actions, kenjougo (謙譲語) humbles your own actions, and teineigo (丁寧語) is standard polite speech using です/ます forms. Teineigo is the baseline for all polite interactions, while sonkeigo and kenjougo are used together in formal and business settings."},
  {"q": "When should I use casual vs polite Japanese?", "a": "Use casual speech (タメ口) only with close friends of similar age, children, and family. Use です/ます (teineigo) with acquaintances, strangers, coworkers, and in public. Use full keigo with clients, superiors, elderly people, and in formal business or ceremonial situations."},
  {"q": "How long does it take to master keigo?", "a": "Basic teineigo takes 3-6 months to become comfortable with. Understanding sonkeigo and kenjougo patterns takes 1-2 years. True mastery of situational keigo use takes 3-5+ years even for dedicated learners. Even native Japanese speakers sometimes struggle with formal keigo."},
  {"q": "What is the most common keigo mistake foreigners make?", "a": "Using sonkeigo (respectful language) for your own actions instead of kenjougo (humble language). For example, saying いらっしゃいます about yourself instead of 参ります. This elevates yourself rather than humbling yourself, which reverses the intended politeness."}
];
